AB  - This paper presents a new explanation of why ‘J-curves’ (i.e. the tendency of the trade balance to deteriorate immediately after a devaluation and to improve only as time passes) may arise. The paper focuses on the consequences of price stickiness: if prices are sticky, the devaluation leads, first, to asn increse in the relative price of tradables, which tends to improve the trade balance, and second, to rising prices of tradables following the devaluation which tends to temporarily worsen the trade balance as a result of intertemporal speculation. If the latter effect dominates, a ‘J-curves’ results.
