DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90054-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900548
AB  - This paper analyzes the interaction of two constraints — foreign currency controls and a minimum wage — on the behavior of a small, industrializing country. The latter is characterized by the large proportion of intermediate inputs in total imports. The main results are the following: (1) the two distortions magnify the adverse effects on employment of a minimum wage; (2) the rationing policy is self-defeating on its own terms; (3) devaluation is almost inevitable, despite the political considerations that make it so difficult; and (4) black markets may be tolerated so openly because they help undo some of the harmful effects noted above.
