DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(89)90056-1
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199689900561
AB  - Sovereign policymakers will opt for too much of the public good if their tax falls partially on foreigners. They myopically calculate that an increase in public spending is only partially financed by a decrease in home consumption; the rest comes from foreign consumption, which they do not care about. This paper presents an example with seignorage taxes. In a two-country model with cash-in-advance constraints, the inefficiency is characterized by an inflation bias, too much public spending, and large fiscal deficits. Curiously, the countries most able to impose such taxes seem to have abstained from doing so.
